<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-10-20T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-10-20T14:00:00-05:00" n="455" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d455">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">832.00 Revolutions/118: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Chargé in Brazil</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-10-20T14:00:00-05:00">October 20, 1930—2
                                p.m.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>71. Consul Pernambuco inquired October 18<note n="7" xml:id="d455fn7">Telegram not printed.</note> whether local <hi rend="italic">de
                                facto</hi> revolutionary Government should be informed regarding
                            forthcoming visit to that port of <hi rend="italic">Pensacola</hi> and
                            whether customary official call on Governor should be arranged for under
                            existing circumstances. Department in reply instructed Consul to inform
                                <hi rend="italic">de facto</hi> Government of visit to Pernambuco
                            but stated that official calls should not be made to revolutionary
                            authorities.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>